statement.p:
If \mathcal{B} = \{ \mb{v}_1 , \ldots, \mb{v}_n \} is a basis for the vector space V then 

                        \left\{ \mb{v}_{i_1} \wedge \cdots \wedge \mb{v}_{i_k} :1 \leq i_1 \lt i_2 \lt \cdots \lt i_k \leq n\right\}

                    is a basis for the k-the wedge product \bigwedge^k V. Furthermore, if k \gt n then \bigwedge^k V is the zero vector space.

subsection.p:
We recall that the absolute value of the determinant expresses the volume of the parallelepiped spanned by the columns, so we can see that the exterior product `knows' about their volume. In fact, the exterior product knows about many other volumes as well if we start with an inner product. In particular, if V has an inner product, we can extend it to define an inner product on \bigwedge^* V. This can be done by taking an orthonormal basis \mathcal{B} = \{\mb{v}_1, \ldots, \mb{v}_n\} of V and making all of their products an orthonormal basis of \bigwedge^* V so that 

            \{ \mb{v}_{i_1} \wedge \cdots \wedge \mb{v}_{i_k} : 1 \leq  i_1 \lt \cdots \lt i_k \leq n, 0 \leq k \leq n \}

        forms an orthonormal basis. To see that this makes sense, we define our inner product more intrinsically as follows.
